ower\n! Torque\n! Valvetrain\n! Top speed\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 2.0 16V\n| [[Renault F-Type engine|F4R]]\n| '''1998 cc'''\n| {{convert|102|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5500 rpm\n| {{convert|188|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3750 rpm\n| DOHC\n| {{convert|180|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.9 dCi\n| [[Renault F-Type engine|F9Q]]\n| '''1870 cc'''\n| {{convert|75|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 4000 rpm\n| {{convert|200|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 1500 rpm\n| SOHC\n| {{convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic II (2003\u20132009)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sc\u00e9nic II\n| image = 2005 Renault Scenic D-Mique DCi 130 E4 1.9.jpg\n| production = 2003\u20132009\n| assembly = France: [[Douai]] ([[Douai Renault Factory|Douai Factory]])\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2685|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault-scenic-14-16v-authentique-basis-5-doors-mpv-5-speed-manual-56681.html|title=Renault Sc\u00e9nic 1.4 16V Authentique Basis - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><br />{{convert|2736|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault-grand-scenic-15-dci-100-authentique-basis-5-doors-mpv-5-speed-manual-56456.html|title=Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic 1.5 dCi 100 Authentique Basis - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4259|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<br /> {{convert|4493|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| width = {{convert|1811|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"scenic_ii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-scenic-2003-14-16v.html|title=RENAULT Scenic - 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"grand_scenic_ii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-grand-scenic-2003-16-16v.html|title=RENAULT Grand Scenic - 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1621|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_ii\"/><br />{{convert|1641|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_ii\"/>\n| weight = \n| related = [[Renault M\u00e9gane]] II\n}}\n[[File:2006 Renault Scenic D-QUE DCi 130 E4 1.9 Rear.jpg|thumb|left|Pre facelift Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic]]\nShortly after the launch of the M\u00e9gane II, an all new Sc\u00e9nic was launched in June 2003. There was also a seven seater [[Compact MPV]] '''Grand Sc\u00e9nic''', with a longer [[wheelbase]] and rear [[overhang (automotive)|overhang]], which has two small child sized seats in the enlarged [[luggage]] area. The '''Grand Sc\u00e9nic''' was officially launched in April 2004.\n\nAs with the M\u00e9gane, the new car employs corporate styling cues and new technology, including the \"Renault Card\" [[remote keyless system|keyless immobiliser]] and an [[parking brake|automatic parking brake]] on certain [[car model|trim levels]]. It integrates [[Light-emitting diode|LEDs]] on all trims since 2006. As with the Sc\u00e9nic I Phase 2, a raised \"M\u00e9gane\" logo appears on the C pillar. \n\nThe car received a different dashboard design to that of the M\u00e9gane, and featured a fully digital [[electroluminescence]] instrument display.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic II includes folding rear passenger seats, each separately adjustable and removable. With integrated [[table (furniture)|table]], a folding front passenger seat (on certain trim levels), [[headlamp|automatic headlights]] and [[windscreen wiper]]s, 'Child minder' [[mirror]], as well as front and rear electric windows.\n\nUnlike its predecessor, the Sc\u00e9nic II was not available at any [[Yanase (car dealership)|Yanase Co., Ltd.]] dealerships, as Yanase had ended its import rights for Renault after Renault had acquired a stake in Nissan when the Sc\u00e9nic I was still in production. Instead, the Sc\u00e9nic II was sold exclusively through Nissan locations.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Facelift===\nLike the M\u00e9gane a few months earlier, the Sc\u00e9nic II underwent a minor [[facelift (automobile)|facelift]] with a revised [[grille]], larger diamond [[badge engineering|badge]], the addition of a \"RENAULT\" word badge on the [[wikt:bootlid|bootlid]] and new wheel designs and interior [[trim package|trim]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Sales commenced in September 2006.\n<gallery>\nFile:2008 Renault Sc\u00e9nic (J84 Phase 2) Expression dCi hatchback (2015-07-14) 01.jpg|Facelifted version\nFile:2008 Renault Sc\u00e9nic (J84 Phase 2) Expression dCi hatchback (2015-07-14) 02.jpg|Facelifted version\n</gallery>\n\n===Sc\u00e9nic Conquest===\n[[File:Renault Scenic Conquest.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Renault Sc\u00e9nic Conquest]]\nIn June 2007, the spiritual successor to the ''RX4'' was revealed in the form of the production ready ''Sc\u00e9nic Conquest''. Although powered by two wheel drive, the Conquest has a body kit, raised ride height and features accessories usually reserved for SUVs.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic III (2009\u20132015)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sc\u00e9nic III\n| image =Renault Sc\u00e9nic (III) \u2013 Frontansicht, 2. Juli 2011, Ratingen.jpg\n| production = 2009\u20132015\n| assembly = France: [[Douai]] ([[Douai Renault Factory|Douai Factory]])\n| related = [[Renault M\u00e9gane]] III\n| engine = 1.2l H5Ft I4 petrol<br>1.5l K9K I4 dCi FAP diesel<br>1.6l R9M I4 dCi FAP diesel<br>1.9l F9Q l4 dCI FAP/non-FAP diesel\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2700|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_iii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-scenic-2009-12-tce-6mt-115-hp.html|title=RENAULT Scenic - 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><br />{{convert|2769|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_iii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-grand-scenic-2009-12-tce-6mt-130-hp.html|title=RENAULT Grand Scenic - 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4343|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_iii\"/><br />{{convert|4559|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_iii\"/>\n| width = {{convert|1844|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1636|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_iii\"/><br />{{convert|1643|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_iii\"/>\n| weight = \n}}\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic III was released in July 2009, while the seven seater 'Grand' version (New Grand Sc\u00e9nic) was released in May 2009. Like the previous Sc\u00e9nic, there is also a seven seater Compact MPV Grand Sc\u00e9nic. Renault also offers the Grand Sc\u00e9nic as a five seater. In 2013, Renault introduced a crossover version of the Sc\u00e9nic, which was called the XMOD. This car has different styling to the normal car.\n\nDifferences such as plastic cladding, raised suspension and even different wheels to the normal spec Sc\u00e9nic.\n\n[[File:Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic III Phase I Grand Mokkabraun Heck.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic (Pre facelift)]]\n\n===Facelift===\n[[File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic Bose Edition ENERGY TCe 130 Start & Stop (III, 2. Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 9. Februar 2014, Velbert.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Sc\u00e9nic Bose Edition ENERGY TCe 130 Start & Stop (Facelift)]]\n[[File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic Paris Deluxe 110 (III, 2. Facelift) \u2013 Frontansicht, 5. Oktober 2013, M\u00fcnster.jpg|thumb|Renault Sc\u00e9nic Deluxe 110 (Facelift)]]\nAn updated Sc\u00e9nic and Grand Sc\u00e9nic was released in March 2013, which features a new interior and exterior styling and driver aids.<ref>{{cite web|title=New cars for 2013|url=http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/new-cars-for-2013-part-2/mpvs--renault---toyota/260534|work=What Car?|publisher=Haymarket Consumer Media|accessdate=2013-03-07|date=2013-03-07}}</ref>\n\nBoth the Sc\u00e9nic and Grand Sc\u00e9nic can be specified with an Efficient Dual Clutch gearbox, mated to the 1.5dci (110&nbsp;bhp) engine.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic IV (2016\u2013present)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sc\u00e9nic IV\n| image = [[File:2017 Renault Scenic Dynamique NAV DCi 1.5 Front.jpg|300px]]<br>[[File:2017 Renault Scenic Dynamique NAV DCi 1.5 Rear.jpg|300px]]\n| production = 2016\u2013present\n| assembly = France: Douai (Douai Factory)\n| transmission = {{ubl |6-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]|6-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|7-speed automatic}}\n| platform = [[Renault\u2013Nissan Common Module Family]] CMF-CD\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2734|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br />{{convert|2804|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| length = {{convert|4406|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br />{{convert|4634|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| width = {{convert|1865|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br />{{convert|1865|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| height = {{convert|1653|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}  <br />{{convert|1660|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| weight = \n| related = [[Renault Espace]] V\n}}\n[[File:2017 Renault Grand Scenic SIG NAV DCi 1.5 Rear.jpg|thumb|left|Grand Scenic]]\n[[File:2017 Renault Scenic Interior.jpg|thumb|left|Interior]]\nA fourth generation Sc\u00e9nic was unveiled at the 2016 [[Geneva Motor Show]]. The car, based on the [[Renault R-Space|R-Space]] concept, is slightly larger than its predecessor, and adds some crossover design elements<ref name=autocar2>{{cite web|title=2016 Renault Scenic makes world debut in Geneva|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motor-shows-geneva-motor-show/2016-renault-scenic-makes-world-debut-geneva|work=Autocar|publisher=Haymarket Consumer Media|accessdate=2016-03-01|date=2016-03-01}}</ref> but, according to Renault, it is still an MPV.<ref>{{cite web|title= #GIMS 2016 : Exclusive world premi\u00e8re for New Sc\u00e9nic at the Geneva Motor Show|url=https://group.renault.com/en/news/blog-renault/gims-2016-exclusive-world-premiere-for-new-scenic-at-the-geneva-motor-show/?adbsc=social_20160301_25866134&adbid=704697475232358400&adbpl=tw&adbpr=16144151|work=Renault Live blog |publisher=Renault|accessdate=2016-03-01|date=2016-03-01|quote=It is a sexier and more modern take on the MPV}}</ref>\n\nIt is powered by six diesel and two petrol engines. For the models with six-speed manual transmission and Energy dCi 110 diesel engines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autodata1.com/en/car/renault/scenic/scenic-iv-15-energy-dci-110-hp-edc|title=Renault Scenic IV 1.5 Energy dCi (110 Hp) EDC|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref> it will incorporate an optional [[Hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid unit]] (Hybrid Assist).<ref name=autocar2/> The Sc\u00e9nic will be offered with manual or double clutch gear box. The Sc\u00e9nic offer a 572 l trunk and the Grand Sc\u00e9nic 765 l with five seats.\n\nThe MKIV Sc\u00e9nic received a five star rating in [[Euro NCAP]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brayleys.co.uk/renault/new-cars/scenic|title=New Renault Sc\u00e9nic Cars for Sale {{!}} New Sc\u00e9nic Cars - Brayley Renault|website=www.brayleys.co.uk|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref> with a range of standard active and passive safety features, including 'Active Emergency Braking System' with 'Pedestrian Detection' making the Renault Sc\u00e9nic the only compact MPV with this feature as standard.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic also features 'Lane Keeping Assist' and 'Fatigue Detection Alert'. Above 31&nbsp;mph, the Sc\u00e9nic can detect fatigue associated driving and alerts the driver, if the driver does not react, it is able to correct the trajectory autonomously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.renault.co.uk/vehicles/new-vehicles/all-new-scenic/equipment.html|title=Features {{!}} All-New SCENIC {{!}} Cars {{!}} Renault UK|website=Renault|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic in the United Kingdom==\nSales of the Sc\u00e9nic in the [[United Kingdom]] began in May 1997, and for the first two years, the Sc\u00e9nic was the only compact MPV sold by an mainstream manufacturer in the United Kingdom, however the [[Vauxhall Zafira]], [[Citro\u00ebn Xsara Picasso]], [[Fiat Multipla]] and the [[Nissan Almera Tino]] were launched in less than five years. In 1997, the ''M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic'' was awarded the ''Car of the Year'' by ''[[What Car?]]''.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic II arrived in showrooms in the country in September 2003. The Sc\u00e9nic III arrived in showrooms in the country in May 2009. The Sc\u00e9nic IV arrived in showrooms in the end of 2016.\n\nIn October 2014, ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear Magazine]]'' placed the Sc\u00e9nic XMOD on its list of ''The Worst Cars You Can Buy Right Now''.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/photos/The-worst-cars-you-can-buy-right-now-2014-10-09 |title=The Worst Cars You Can Buy Right Now |magazine=[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]] Magazine |date=2014-10-09 |accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref> The facelifted versions could be specified with the R Link touchscreen system, that includes a digital radio.<ref>{{cite web|title=R-LINK {{!}} Multimedia {{!}} Owner Services {{!}} Renault UK|url=https://www.renault.co.uk/services/multimedia/r-link.html|website=Renault}}</ref>\n\n==Recall==\nElectronic defects have caused Renault to issue two recalls. The first, in October 2009, was because of the dashboard could stop functioning, leaving drivers without the ability to gauge their speed, fuel tank, direction indicators or anything as all instruments were totally electronic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/watchdog/2009/10/renault_get_lost_on_a_scenic_r.html |title=Renault gets lost on the Sc\u00e9nic route |date=2009-10-07 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2011-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509215912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/watchdog/2009/10/renault_get_lost_on_a_scenic_r.html |archivedate=2011-05-09 }}</ref>\n\nAt first drivers had to replace this part at their own expense, but eventually, because of media pressure, Renault UK and Ireland said that they would reimburse customers up to a set limit. No reimburse was implemented by Renault in Finland where several independent workshops launched an affordable priced fixing of blanked Sc\u00e9nic panels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand scenicin mittaristo|url=http://keskustelu.suomi24.fi/node/5838779|publisher=Suomi24|date=2008-05-21|accessdate=2012-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe cause of the unexpected instrument panel blankening originated from some defective soldering which caused the power transistor to overheat and fail. The fault occurred in Sc\u00e9nic II cars made between 2003 and 2006. The second, in August 2010, was because the electric handbrake could sometimes engage on its own while the car was in motion.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1300211/Renault-recalls-66-000-British-cars-faulty-handbrake.html |title= Renault recalls 66,000 British cars over handbrake which can apply itself while being driven\n|date=2010-08-04 |newspaper=Daily Mail |accessdate=2011-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Alternative propulsion==\nThe [[Cleanova]] III, presented in the 2005 [[Geneva Auto Show]], is based on a Sc\u00e9nic platform.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Renault Modus]], the [[mini MPV]] of the manufacturer\n*[[Renault Espace]], the [[minivan|large MPV]] of the manufacturer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Renault Sc\u00e9nic}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.renault.co.uk/vehicles/new-vehicles/all-new-scenic.html}} (UK)\n*{{Official website|https://www.renault.co.uk/vehicles/new-vehicles/all-new-grand-scenic.html}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic - UK)\n\n{{Renault vehicles timeline 1980 to date, Western European and North American market}}\n{{Renault}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renault Scenic}}\n[[Category:Renault vehicles|Scenic]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP small MPVs]]\n[[Category:Compact MPVs]]\n[[Category:Minivans]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]] \n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Renault Sc\u00e9nic\n| aka = Renault M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic (1996\u20131999)<br />Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic (2004\u2013present)\n| image = File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic IV in a slightly unusual and not unpleasant shade of blue.jpg\n| caption = Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic \n| manufacturer = [[Renault]]\n| production = 1996\u2013present\n| class = [[Compact MPV]] ([[M-segment|M]])\n| body_style = 5-door [[Minivan|MPV]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel-drive]] or [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|four-wheel-drive]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Renault Sc\u00e9nic''' is a [[compact MPV|compact multi-purpose vehicle]] (MPV) produced by [[France|French]] automaker [[Renault]], the first to be labelled as such in [[Europe]]. It is based on the [[chassis]] of the [[Renault M\u00e9gane|M\u00e9gane]] [[compact car|small family car]]. It became the 1997 [[European Car of the Year]] on its launch in November 1996.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewind to 1997: Renault Megane Scenic.|url=http://www.quicks.co.uk/news/2013/rewind-1997-renault-megane-scenic/|publisher=Quicks|accessdate=10 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140117214001/http://www.quicks.co.uk/news/2013/rewind-1997-renault-megane-scenic/|archivedate=17 January 2014}}</ref> \n\nThe second, third and fourth generations have a model called '''Grand Sc\u00e9nic''', which has seven seats rather than five. From the fourth generation (2016), the Sc\u00e9nic now utilizes three/four bench rear seats instead of three individual rear seats used in previous three generations, due to cost-cutting measures.__TOC__{{Clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic I (1996\u20132003)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic & Sc\u00e9nic I\n| image = Renault M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic I Phase I.JPG\n| caption = 1996\u20131999 Renault M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic\n| production = 1996\u20132003\n| engine = 1.4 L [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault/renault-megane-scenic-5-doors-mpv-748/|title=Renault M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><br />1.4 L ''[[Multi-valve|16-valve]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<ref name=\"scenic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault/renault-scenic-5-doors-mpv-802/|title=Renault Sc\u00e9nic - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><br />1.6 L [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<br />1.6 L ''[[Multi-valve|16-valve]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<br />2.0 L [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<br />2.0 L ''[[Multi-valve|16-valve]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<ref name=\"scenic\"/><br />1.9 L ''[[Indirect injection|D]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Diesel engine|diesel]])<br />1.9 L ''[[Indirect injection|dT]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Diesel engine|diesel]])<br />1.9 L ''[[Indirect injection|dTi]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Diesel engine|diesel]])<br />1.9 L ''[[Common rail|dCi]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Diesel engine|diesel]])<ref name=\"scenic\"/>\n| transmission = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br />4-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2580|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic, Sc\u00e9nic)<br />{{convert|2624|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic RX4)<ref name=\"scenic_rx4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault-scenic-rx4-19-dci-5-doors-mpv-5-speed-manual-56905.html|title=Renault Sc\u00e9nic RX4 1.9 dCi - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4168|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic, Sc\u00e9nic)<br />{{convert|4444|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic RX4)<ref name=\"scenic_rx4\"/>\n| width = {{convert|1719|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic, Sc\u00e9nic)<br />{{convert|1785|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic RX4)<ref name=\"scenic_rx4\"/>\n| height = {{convert|1609|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic, Sc\u00e9nic)<br />{{convert|1730|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic RX4)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-scenic-rx4-2000-20-16v.html|title=RENAULT Scenic RX4 - 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| weight = \n| related = [[Renault M\u00e9gane]] I\n| aka = Beijing Fengjing (BJ6410)<br/ >Kish Khodro Veek\n}}\n[[File:Renault Megane-Scenic (10740342486).jpg|thumb|left|Pre facelift Renault Megane Scenic]]\nThe '''M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic''' can be traced back to a [[concept car]] designed under the supervision of Anne Asensio, then designer at Renault. The Sc\u00e9nic was mechanically identical to the M\u00e9gane hatchback (itself based on the older [[Renault 19|R19]]). The 1.4&nbsp;L, 1.6&nbsp;L \"Energy\", 1.8&nbsp;L \"F Type\" petrol and 1.9&nbsp;L diesel engines were shared with the hatchback range.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic was marketed as a [[minivan|multi-purpose vehicle]], in a smaller size lower price of such vehicles as Renault's own [[Renault Espace|Espace]]. It was launched in November 1996.\n\nRenault underestimated the market demand that the Sc\u00e9nic would have \u2014 predicting that it would be a niche model with only 450 produced a day. Production at the company's Douai plant would eventually peak at nearly 2,500 cars a day.\n\n===Facelift===\n[[File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic I Phase II silver.JPG|thumb|left|Facelifted Renault Sc\u00e9nic]] \n[[File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic 002.JPG|thumb|left|Facelifted Renault Sc\u00e9nic]]\nAlong with the M\u00e9gane hatchback, the Sc\u00e9nic underwent a major frontal restyle in September 1999, and the newer 16 valve engines were introduced. The front end was quite a bit different from the M\u00e9gane counterpart, and there were also redesigned rear lights.\n\nFrom the time of this restyle, it became officially known as the '''Renault Sc\u00e9nic''', although a small \"M\u00e9gane\" badge still appeared on the rear door signifying the car's origin. This model was built in [[Brazil]] with [[flexible-fuel vehicle|flexible fuel engines]]. Production ended in June 2003.\n\nThe Phase 2 allowed the Sc\u00e9nic to be separate from the M\u00e9gane and its predecessor by introducing improvements, such as a storage compartment on the dashboard, and a separate opening rear window on the tailgate. Another small improvement with the Sc\u00e9nic were the rear head restraints, which were fixed over the back of the seat rather than being upright. This increased rear visibility.\n\n===Sc\u00e9nic RX4===\n[[File:2001 Renault Sc\u00e9nic RX4 (J64 Phase 2) Privilege hatchback (2015-07-03) 01.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Sc\u00e9nic RX4 (2000\u20132003)]]\n[[File:2001 Renault Sc\u00e9nic RX4 (J64 Phase 2) Privilege hatchback (2015-07-03) 02.jpg|left|thumb|Renault Sc\u00e9nic RX4 (2000\u20132003)]]\nRenault developed a [[four-wheel drive]] derivative of the original Sc\u00e9nic, the '''Sc\u00e9nic RX4''', launched in 2000 in both LHD and RHD format. Featuring a viscous, multi disc central differential designed by Austrian specialists [[Steyr Daimler Puch]], it offered part time four wheel drive. The rear suspension was re engineered and the suspension was strengthened. \n\nIt also used five wheel nuts, as opposed to four on the standard Sc\u00e8nic.\n\nThe new rear suspension now occupied part of the space that was used for the spare wheel well and led to the spare tyre being placed on the rear hatch. The RX4 rode higher with increased suspension travel and larger wheels.\n\nWhile these changes provided better ground clearance, the RX4 was offered with 2.0 litre petrol and 1.9 dci diesel engines, both already known from the M\u00e9gane. Production of the RX4 ceased in 2003, with no direct successor, until the arrival of the ''Sc\u00e9nic Conquest'' in 2007.\n\