 speed\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 2.0 16V\n| [[Renault F-Type engine|F4R]]\n| '''1998 cc'''\n| {{convert|102|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5500 rpm\n| {{convert|188|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3750 rpm\n| DOHC\n| {{convert|180|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.9 dCi\n| [[Renault F-Type engine|F9Q]]\n| '''1870 cc'''\n| {{convert|75|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 4000 rpm\n| {{convert|200|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 1500 rpm\n| SOHC\n| {{convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic II (2003\u20132009)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sc\u00e9nic II\n| image = 2005 Renault Scenic D-Mique DCi 130 E4 1.9.jpg\n| production = 2003\u20132009\n| assembly = France: [[Douai]] ([[Douai Renault Factory|Douai Factory]])\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2685|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault-scenic-14-16v-authentique-basis-5-doors-mpv-5-speed-manual-56681.html|title=Renault Sc\u00e9nic 1.4 16V Authentique Basis - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><br />{{convert|2736|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-types.com/renault-grand-scenic-15-dci-100-authentique-basis-5-doors-mpv-5-speed-manual-56456.html|title=Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic 1.5 dCi 100 Authentique Basis - 5-doors, mpv|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4259|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<br /> {{convert|4493|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| width = {{convert|1811|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"scenic_ii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-scenic-2003-14-16v.html|title=RENAULT Scenic - 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"grand_scenic_ii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-grand-scenic-2003-16-16v.html|title=RENAULT Grand Scenic - 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1621|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_ii\"/><br />{{convert|1641|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_ii\"/>\n| weight = \n| related = [[Renault M\u00e9gane]] II\n}}\n[[File:2006 Renault Scenic D-QUE DCi 130 E4 1.9 Rear.jpg|thumb|left|Pre facelift Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic]]\nShortly after the launch of the M\u00e9gane II, an all new Sc\u00e9nic was launched in June 2003. There was also a seven seater [[Compact MPV]] '''Grand Sc\u00e9nic''', with a longer [[wheelbase]] and rear [[overhang (automotive)|overhang]], which has two small child sized seats in the enlarged [[luggage]] area. The '''Grand Sc\u00e9nic''' was officially launched in April 2004.\n\nAs with the M\u00e9gane, the new car employs corporate styling cues and new technology, including the \"Renault Card\" [[remote keyless system|keyless immobiliser]] and an [[parking brake|automatic parking brake]] on certain [[car model|trim levels]]. It integrates [[Light-emitting diode|LEDs]] on all trims since 2006. As with the Sc\u00e9nic I Phase 2, a raised \"M\u00e9gane\" logo appears on the C pillar. \n\nThe car received a different dashboard design to that of the M\u00e9gane, and featured a fully digital [[electroluminescence]] instrument display.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic II includes folding rear passenger seats, each separately adjustable and removable. With integrated [[table (furniture)|table]], a folding front passenger seat (on certain trim levels), [[headlamp|automatic headlights]] and [[windscreen wiper]]s, 'Child minder' [[mirror]], as well as front and rear electric windows.\n\nUnlike its predecessor, the Sc\u00e9nic II was not available at any [[Yanase (car dealership)|Yanase Co., Ltd.]] dealerships, as Yanase had ended its import rights for Renault after Renault had acquired a stake in Nissan when the Sc\u00e9nic I was still in production. Instead, the Sc\u00e9nic II was sold exclusively through Nissan locations.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Facelift===\nLike the M\u00e9gane a few months earlier, the Sc\u00e9nic II underwent a minor [[facelift (automobile)|facelift]] with a revised [[grille]], larger diamond [[badge engineering|badge]], the addition of a \"RENAULT\" word badge on the [[wikt:bootlid|bootlid]] and new wheel designs and interior [[trim package|trim]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Sales commenced in September 2006.\n<gallery>\nFile:2008 Renault Sc\u00e9nic (J84 Phase 2) Expression dCi hatchback (2015-07-14) 01.jpg|Facelifted version\nFile:2008 Renault Sc\u00e9nic (J84 Phase 2) Expression dCi hatchback (2015-07-14) 02.jpg|Facelifted version\n</gallery>\n\n===Sc\u00e9nic Conquest===\n[[File:Renault Scenic Conquest.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Renault Sc\u00e9nic Conquest]]\nIn June 2007, the spiritual successor to the ''RX4'' was revealed in the form of the production ready ''Sc\u00e9nic Conquest''. Although powered by two wheel drive, the Conquest has a body kit, raised ride height and features accessories usually reserved for SUVs.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic III (2009\u20132015)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sc\u00e9nic III\n| image =Renault Sc\u00e9nic (III) \u2013 Frontansicht, 2. Juli 2011, Ratingen.jpg\n| production = 2009\u20132015\n| assembly = France: [[Douai]] ([[Douai Renault Factory|Douai Factory]])\n| related = [[Renault M\u00e9gane]] III\n| engine = 1.2l H5Ft I4 petrol<br>1.5l K9K I4 dCi FAP diesel<br>1.6l R9M I4 dCi FAP diesel<br>1.9l F9Q l4 dCI FAP/non-FAP diesel\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2700|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_iii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-scenic-2009-12-tce-6mt-115-hp.html|title=RENAULT Scenic - 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><br />{{convert|2769|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_iii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/engine/renault-grand-scenic-2009-12-tce-6mt-130-hp.html|title=RENAULT Grand Scenic - 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013|work=autoevolution|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4343|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_iii\"/><br />{{convert|4559|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_iii\"/>\n| width = {{convert|1844|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1636|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"scenic_iii\"/><br />{{convert|1643|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)<ref name=\"grand_scenic_iii\"/>\n| weight = \n}}\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic III was released in July 2009, while the seven seater 'Grand' version (New Grand Sc\u00e9nic) was released in May 2009. Like the previous Sc\u00e9nic, there is also a seven seater Compact MPV Grand Sc\u00e9nic. Renault also offers the Grand Sc\u00e9nic as a five seater. In 2013, Renault introduced a crossover version of the Sc\u00e9nic, which was called the XMOD. This car has different styling to the normal car.\n\nDifferences such as plastic cladding, raised suspension and even different wheels to the normal spec Sc\u00e9nic.\n\n[[File:Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic III Phase I Grand Mokkabraun Heck.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Grand Sc\u00e9nic (Pre facelift)]]\n\n===Facelift===\n[[File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic Bose Edition ENERGY TCe 130 Start & Stop (III, 2. Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 9. Februar 2014, Velbert.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Sc\u00e9nic Bose Edition ENERGY TCe 130 Start & Stop (Facelift)]]\n[[File:Renault Sc\u00e9nic Paris Deluxe 110 (III, 2. Facelift) \u2013 Frontansicht, 5. Oktober 2013, M\u00fcnster.jpg|thumb|Renault Sc\u00e9nic Deluxe 110 (Facelift)]]\nAn updated Sc\u00e9nic and Grand Sc\u00e9nic was released in March 2013, which features a new interior and exterior styling and driver aids.<ref>{{cite web|title=New cars for 2013|url=http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/new-cars-for-2013-part-2/mpvs--renault---toyota/260534|work=What Car?|publisher=Haymarket Consumer Media|accessdate=2013-03-07|date=2013-03-07}}</ref>\n\nBoth the Sc\u00e9nic and Grand Sc\u00e9nic can be specified with an Efficient Dual Clutch gearbox, mated to the 1.5dci (110&nbsp;bhp) engine.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic IV (2016\u2013present)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sc\u00e9nic IV\n| image = [[File:2017 Renault Scenic Dynamique NAV DCi 1.5 Front.jpg|300px]]<br>[[File:2017 Renault Scenic Dynamique NAV DCi 1.5 Rear.jpg|300px]]\n| production = 2016\u2013present\n| assembly = France: Douai (Douai Factory)\n| transmission = {{ubl |6-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]|6-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|7-speed automatic}}\n| platform = [[Renault\u2013Nissan Common Module Family]] CMF-CD\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2734|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br />{{convert|2804|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| length = {{convert|4406|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br />{{convert|4634|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| width = {{convert|1865|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br />{{convert|1865|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| height = {{convert|1653|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}  <br />{{convert|1660|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic)\n| weight = \n| related = [[Renault Espace]] V\n}}\n[[File:2017 Renault Grand Scenic SIG NAV DCi 1.5 Rear.jpg|thumb|left|Grand Scenic]]\n[[File:2017 Renault Scenic Interior.jpg|thumb|left|Interior]]\nA fourth generation Sc\u00e9nic was unveiled at the 2016 [[Geneva Motor Show]]. The car, based on the [[Renault R-Space|R-Space]] concept, is slightly larger than its predecessor, and adds some crossover design elements<ref name=autocar2>{{cite web|title=2016 Renault Scenic makes world debut in Geneva|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motor-shows-geneva-motor-show/2016-renault-scenic-makes-world-debut-geneva|work=Autocar|publisher=Haymarket Consumer Media|accessdate=2016-03-01|date=2016-03-01}}</ref> but, according to Renault, it is still an MPV.<ref>{{cite web|title= #GIMS 2016 : Exclusive world premi\u00e8re for New Sc\u00e9nic at the Geneva Motor Show|url=https://group.renault.com/en/news/blog-renault/gims-2016-exclusive-world-premiere-for-new-scenic-at-the-geneva-motor-show/?adbsc=social_20160301_25866134&adbid=704697475232358400&adbpl=tw&adbpr=16144151|work=Renault Live blog |publisher=Renault|accessdate=2016-03-01|date=2016-03-01|quote=It is a sexier and more modern take on the MPV}}</ref>\n\nIt is powered by six diesel and two petrol engines. For the models with six-speed manual transmission and Energy dCi 110 diesel engines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autodata1.com/en/car/renault/scenic/scenic-iv-15-energy-dci-110-hp-edc|title=Renault Scenic IV 1.5 Energy dCi (110 Hp) EDC|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref> it will incorporate an optional [[Hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid unit]] (Hybrid Assist).<ref name=autocar2/> The Sc\u00e9nic will be offered with manual or double clutch gear box. The Sc\u00e9nic offer a 572 l trunk and the Grand Sc\u00e9nic 765 l with five seats.\n\nThe MKIV Sc\u00e9nic received a five star rating in [[Euro NCAP]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brayleys.co.uk/renault/new-cars/scenic|title=New Renault Sc\u00e9nic Cars for Sale {{!}} New Sc\u00e9nic Cars - Brayley Renault|website=www.brayleys.co.uk|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref> with a range of standard active and passive safety features, including 'Active Emergency Braking System' with 'Pedestrian Detection' making the Renault Sc\u00e9nic the only compact MPV with this feature as standard.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic also features 'Lane Keeping Assist' and 'Fatigue Detection Alert'. Above 31&nbsp;mph, the Sc\u00e9nic can detect fatigue associated driving and alerts the driver, if the driver does not react, it is able to correct the trajectory autonomously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.renault.co.uk/vehicles/new-vehicles/all-new-scenic/equipment.html|title=Features {{!}} All-New SCENIC {{!}} Cars {{!}} Renault UK|website=Renault|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sc\u00e9nic in the United Kingdom==\nSales of the Sc\u00e9nic in the [[United Kingdom]] began in May 1997, and for the first two years, the Sc\u00e9nic was the only compact MPV sold by an mainstream manufacturer in the United Kingdom, however the [[Vauxhall Zafira]], [[Citro\u00ebn Xsara Picasso]], [[Fiat Multipla]] and the [[Nissan Almera Tino]] were launched in less than five years. In 1997, the ''M\u00e9gane Sc\u00e9nic'' was awarded the ''Car of the Year'' by ''[[What Car?]]''.\n\nThe Sc\u00e9nic II arrived in showrooms in the country in September 2003. The Sc\u00e9nic III arrived in showrooms in the country in May 2009. The Sc\u00e9nic IV arrived in showrooms in the end of 2016.\n\nIn October 2014, ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear Magazine]]'' placed the Sc\u00e9nic XMOD on its list of ''The Worst Cars You Can Buy Right Now''.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/photos/The-worst-cars-you-can-buy-right-now-2014-10-09 |title=The Worst Cars You Can Buy Right Now |magazine=[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]] Magazine |date=2014-10-09 |accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref> The facelifted versions could be specified with the R Link touchscreen system, that includes a digital radio.<ref>{{cite web|title=R-LINK {{!}} Multimedia {{!}} Owner Services {{!}} Renault UK|url=https://www.renault.co.uk/services/multimedia/r-link.html|website=Renault}}</ref>\n\n==Recall==\nElectronic defects have caused Renault to issue two recalls. The first, in October 2009, was because of the dashboard could stop functioning, leaving drivers without the ability to gauge their speed, fuel tank, direction indicators or anything as all instruments were totally electronic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/watchdog/2009/10/renault_get_lost_on_a_scenic_r.html |title=Renault gets lost on the Sc\u00e9nic route |date=2009-10-07 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2011-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509215912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/watchdog/2009/10/renault_get_lost_on_a_scenic_r.html |archivedate=2011-05-09 }}</ref>\n\nAt first drivers had to replace this part at their own expense, but eventually, because of media pressure, Renault UK and Ireland said that they would reimburse customers up to a set limit. No reimburse was implemented by Renault in Finland where several independent workshops launched an affordable priced fixing of blanked Sc\u00e9nic panels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand scenicin mittaristo|url=http://keskustelu.suomi24.fi/node/5838779|publisher=Suomi24|date=2008-05-21|accessdate=2012-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe cause of the unexpected instrument panel blankening originated from some defective soldering which caused the power transistor to overheat and fail. The fault occurred in Sc\u00e9nic II cars made between 2003 and 2006. The second, in August 2010, was because the electric handbrake could sometimes engage on its own while the car was in motion.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1300211/Renault-recalls-66-000-British-cars-faulty-handbrake.html |title= Renault recalls 66,000 British cars over handbrake which can apply itself while being driven\n|date=2010-08-04 |newspaper=Daily Mail |accessdate=2011-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Alternative propulsion==\nThe [[Cleanova]] III, presented in the 2005 [[Geneva Auto Show]], is based on a Sc\u00e9nic platform.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Renault Modus]], the [[mini MPV]] of the manufacturer\n*[[Renault Espace]], the [[minivan|large MPV]] of the manufacturer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Renault Sc\u00e9nic}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.renault.co.uk/vehicles/new-vehicles/all-new-scenic.html}} (UK)\n*{{Official website|https://www.renault.co.uk/vehicles/new-vehicles/all-new-grand-scenic.html}} (Grand Sc\u00e9nic - UK)\n\n{{Renault vehicles timeline 1980 to date, Western European and North American market}}\n{{Renault}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renault Scenic}}\n[[Category:Renault vehicles|Scenic]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP small MPVs]]\n[[Category:Compact MPVs]]\n[[Category:Minivans]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]] \n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "BLakerman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a photo of the Scenic concept car", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renault_Sc%C3%A9nic"}
{"title_page": "Remington Steele", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Remington Steele\n| image = Remington Steele logo black.svg\n| genre = {{unbulleted list|[[Comedy-drama]]|[[Police procedural|Detective procedural]]|[[Action fiction|Action]]/[[Adventure fiction|adventure]]|[[Crime fiction]]|[[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]|Romance}}\n| camera =\n| runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials) \n| creator = [[Robert Butler (director)|Robert Butler]]<br />Michael Gleason\n| developer = \n| producer = Kevin Inch<br />Gareth Davies<br />Richard DeRoy\n| executive_producer = Michael Gleason\n| presenter = [[MTM Enterprises]]\n| starring = [[Stephanie Zimbalist]]<br />[[Pierce Brosnan]]<br />[[Doris Roberts]]\n| narrated = [[Stephanie Zimbalist]] in character as Laura Holt (Season 1 titles only)\n| theme_music_composer = [[Henry Mancini]]; incidental music by Richard Lewis Warren\n| opentheme = \"The ''Remington Steele'' Theme\", composed by Henry Mancini\n| endtheme = \"Laura Holt's Tune\", composed by Henry Mancini\n| company = [[MTM Enterprises]]\n| distributor = [[MTM Enterprises|MTM Television Distribution Group]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| location = [[Los Angeles]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| network = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format = Color\n| audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|1982|10|1}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|1987|2|17}}\n| num_seasons = 5\n| num_episodes = 94\n| list_episodes = List of Remington Steele episodes \n}}\n\n'''''Remington Steele''''' is an American [[police procedural]] [[crime drama]] television series co-created by [[Robert Butler (director)|Robert Butler]] and Michael Gleason. The series, starring [[Stephanie Zimbalist]] and [[Pierce Brosnan]], was produced by [[MTM Enterprises]] and first broadcast on the [[NBC]] network from October 10, [[1982 in television|1982]] to February 17, [[1987 in television|1987]]. The series blended the genres of romantic comedy, drama, detective procedural and (towards the end of the series) international political intrigue and espionage.\n\n''Remington Steele's'' premise is that Laura Holt, a licensed [[private investigator]] played by Stephanie Zimbalist, opened a detective agency under her own name but found potential clients refused to hire a woman, no matter how qualified. To solve the problem, Laura invents a fictitious male superior she names Remington Steele. Through a series of events in the first episode, \"License to Steele\", Pierce Brosnan's character, a former thief and con man (whose real name even ''he'' proves not to know and is never revealed), assumes the identity of Remington Steele. Behind the scenes, a power struggle ensues between Laura and Steele as to who is really in charge, while the two carry on a casual romantic relationship.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Stephanie Zimbalist]] as Laura Holt\n*[[Pierce Brosnan]] as Special Agent Ben Pearson/Remington Steele\n*[[Doris Roberts]] as Mildred Krebs (from Season 2 onward) \n*[[Janet DeMay]] as Bernice Foxe (Season 1)\n*[[James Read]] as Murphy Michaels (Season 1)\n*[[Jack Scalia]] as Tony Roselli (Season 5)\nOther recurring actors included: \n*[[Cassandra Harris]] (late wife of Pierce Brosnan) as Felicia, one of Steele's old flames (3 episodes), and Anna, a mysterious woman from Steele's past (1 episode)\n*[[Efrem Zimbalist Jr.]] as Daniel Chalmers, a charming con man who was Steele's mentor and later revealed to be his biological father\n*[[Beverly Garland]] as Abigail Holt, Laura's mother\n*[[Gary Frank (actor)|Gary Frank]] as Detective James Jarvis, a less-than-competent police detective who more often than not falsely accused the principal characters and their clients of murder\n*[[Michael Constantine]] as George Edward Mulch, a businessman with far-fetched ideas looking only for fame and fortune\n*[[James Tolkan]] as Norman Keyes, an insurance investigator bent on proving Steele to be a fraud\n*[[Blake Clark]] as Fred, the Chauffeur\nGuest stars included:\n*[[Louie Anderson]], \"Steele Spawning\", Season 4\n*[[Tom Baker]] \"Hounded Steele\" Season 2\n*[[Judith Barsi]], \"Suburban Steele\", Season 4\n*[[Thom Bray]], \"Signed, Steeled and Delivered\", Season 1\n*[[Delta Burke]], \"Altared Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Daniel Davis]], \"Gourmet Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Geena Davis]], \"Steele in the Chips\", Season 3\n*[[Sarah Douglas (actress)|Sarah Douglas]], \"Steele Hanging In There\", Season 5\n*[[Whitey Ford]] and [[Mickey Mantle]], \"Second Base Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Conrad Janis]], \"Stronger Than Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Jeffrey Jones]], \"A Steele at Any Price\", Season 2\n*[[Jane Kaczmarek]], \"Altared Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Dorothy Lamour]], \"Cast in Steele\", Season 3\n*[[John Larroquette]], \"Breath of Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Judith Light]], \"Dreams of Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Rose Marie]], \"Steele in the Spotlight\", Season 4\n*[[A Martinez]], \"High Flying Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Virginia Mayo]], \"Cast of Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Beverlee McKinsey]], \"Vintage Steele\", Season 1\n*[[Lloyd Nolan]], \"Cast in Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Annie Potts]], \"Steele Crazy After All These Years\", Season 1\n*[[Faith Prince]], \"Scene Steelers\", Season 2\n*[[Ford Rainey]], \u201dSmall Town Steele\u201d, Season 2\n*[[Paul Reiser]], \"A Good Night's Steele\", Season 1\n*[[Peter Scolari]], \"Steele Waters Run Deep\", Season 1\n*[[Jean Smart]], \"Steele in the Chips\", Season 3\n*[[Sharon Stone]], \"Steele Crazy After All These Years\", Season 1\n*[[John van Dreelen]], \u201dSteele Threads, Season 2\n*[[Barry Van Dyke]], \"Steele Belted\", Season 1\n*[[Guy Boyd (actor)|Guy Boyd]], \"Hearts of Steele\", \"Steele Framed\", \"Elegy of Steele\", Season 1 & 2\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Remington Steele episodes}}\n{{:List of Remington Steele episodes}}\n\n==Significance and influence==\n''Remington Steele'' is best known for having launched the career of [[Pierce Brosnan]]<ref>Mark Murphy and Frank Swertlow, \"Why Would I Do a Poster? Would Robert De Niro?\", ''TV Guide'', June 9, 1984</ref> and for serving as a forerunner of the similar, edgier series ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]],''<ref>Robert J. Thompson, ''Television's Second Golden Age'' (New York: Continuum, 1996) 112-113.</ref> and was also an influential part of television history in its own right. Recent evaluations, in the wake of the show's full release on DVD, conclude that ''Steele'' was solidly crafted, well-acted and groundbreaking in its own way.<ref>Emily VanDerWerff, \"Primer: 1980s Television Dramas\", page 2, \"In the Genre Trenches\", A.V. Club, April 28, 2011 [http://www.avclub.com/articles/1980s-tv-dramas,55221/2/ The A.V. Club]; see also Cory Barker, \"Test Pilot: File #20 Remington Steele\", TV Surveillance blog, August 3, 2011, [http://tvsurveillance.com/2011/08/03/test-pilot-file-20-remington-steele/ Tvsurveillance.com]</ref> Other recent evaluations have also noted that series has aged better than some other series of its time and genre.<ref>Lucy Mangan, \"Cable Girl\", ''The Guardian'' (U.K.), August 11, 2008, [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/aug/12/television2 The Guardian]</ref>\n\n===Innovations===\n''Remington Steele'' referenced [[film noir]] in the mystery storylines.<ref>Michael Gleason, \"Comedy and Old Movies\" special feature ''Remington Steele,'' season 1, disc 3 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005), DVD</ref> It subverted 1970s detective show conventions by telling its stories from the point of view of an independent, professional woman.<ref>Michael Ryan, Sound on Sight magazine, October 26, 2011, [http://www.soundonsight.org/obsessive-compulsive-procedural-2-prime-suspect/ Soundonsight.org]</ref> At a time when hour-long series were serious and half-hour series were humorous, ''Steele'' incorporated multiple styles of comedy into the standard detective format.<ref>Michael Gleason and Jeff Melvoin audio commentary, \"Diced Steele\", ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 3 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2006), DVD</ref> It pioneered the slowly evolving \"will they or won't they\" relationship arc that is now common to television drama of all genres.<ref>Noel Holston, \"Sexual Tension Teases Stars and Viewers,\" ''Orlando Sentinel'', February 9, 1986, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-02-09/entertainment/8601100825_1_remington-steele-angela-bower-pierce-brosnan Chicago Tribune]</ref><ref>Kate Aurthur, \"Do It Already,\" Slate.com, April 3, 2006, [http://www.slate.com/id/2139176/ Slate]</ref>\n\n===Laura Holt as role model===\nIn an interview recorded in 2005 for a DVD special feature, ''Remington Steele'' co-creator Michael Gleason and star Stephanie Zimbalist discuss the large number of women who have approached them over the years to express their appreciation for the character of Laura Holt. Speaking of the women she meets, Zimbalist said \"They are extraordinary women.... They are interesting. They do interesting things. They are smart. They're independent. They're sort of, what my character was \u2013 and I meet them all the time.\"<ref>Michael Gleason and Stephanie Zimbalist in \"Steele Together\", ''Remington Steele'', season 2, disc 3 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005), DVD, 5:52 \u2013 7:12.</ref> Also in 2005, Robin Rauzi published an article in the ''Los Angeles Times'' saying that Laura Holt was her hero.<ref>Robin Rauzi, \"Following in Her Fedora; A Laura Holt Fan Goes on Location, Sort of, With Her Hero\", ''Los Angeles Times'', September 8, 2005.</ref> In a subsequent interview Rauzi elaborated, saying that Laura \"was one of the only examples of an unmarried modern career woman on TV that I could identify with at that time\" and that Laura \"didn\u2019t seem that far away from who I was and who I could be.\" Rauzi concludes, \"I\u2019ve decided to stop being embarrassed to say ''Remington Steele'' changed my life. It did and for the better.\"<ref>Robin Rauzi in \"Steele Fanatics\", ''Remington Steele'', season 4, disc 1 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2006), DVD, 3:15 \u2013 4:20.</ref>\n\n==Series history==\n\n===Development===\n''Remington Steele\u2019s'' initial premise was conceived in 1969 by long-time television director [[Robert Butler (director)|Robert Butler]]<ref>Robert Butler interview, chapter 7, Archive of American Television, January 14, 2004, [http://emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/robert-butler/ Emmytvlegends.org]</ref> as a series featuring a solo female private investigator. Butler pitched the idea to [[Grant Tinker]] before he was head of [[MTM Enterprises|MTM]], but Tinker felt the series was ahead of its time. In January 1980, following the success of several sitcoms featuring working women, including the groundbreaking ''Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' Butler and Tinker, now head of MTM, revived the concept.<ref>''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 23, 43.</ref> MTM Vice President of Programming Stu Erwin felt Butler's concept was only \"half a show\" and suggested that Butler work with veteran writer Michael Gleason<ref>Michael Gleason [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0322327/ IMDb]</ref> to expand the premise. Imagining Holt's fictional boss, Gleason proposed to Butler, \u201cWouldn\u2019t it be great if he showed up and made her crazy?\u201d<ref>Robert Butler, Stu Erwin, and Michael Gleason, \u201cMaking of Remington Steele Season One,\u201d ''Remington Steele'', season 1, disc 1 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005), DVD, 0:17 \u2013 1:52.</ref> In 1981, Gleason, Butler, Erwin and Tinker pitched the series to NBC and were initially rejected by executives who failed to \"get\" the premise. Shortly thereafter, Tinker left MTM to become chairman of NBC, then the number-three network, and subsequently a pilot was ordered.<ref>Michael Gleason, \"Foreword\" in ''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 16-17.</ref>\n\nStephanie Zimbalist, an established actress with roles in several television movies, was approached for the role of Laura Holt. At first she turned the series down, not wishing to be tied down to one show, but had a late-night change of heart.<ref>Michael Leahy, \"The Time: 5:30 A.M., Her Thought: 'I must be an Idiot'\", ''[[TV Guide]]'', November 20, 1982.</ref> Pierce Brosnan (best known then for his role in ''[[Manions of America|The Manions of America]]'') auditioned for the role of Remington Steele but was initially refused by NBC executives who were concerned that Brosnan was a relative unknown in America. MTM's Stu Erwin stood firm in a face-to-face meeting with NBC executive [[Brandon Tartikoff]] and Tartikoff relented.<ref>''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 28.</ref>\n\nOriginally, NBC asked for a pilot that imagined the series six months into its run, with the characters already working together in the detective agency. This pilot was produced in February and March 1982 and was eventually aired with revisions as \"Tempered Steele\". NBC had some concerns about audience confusion over this episode, but ultimately agreed to schedule the series for the 1982-83 season.<ref>''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective,'' Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 29-30.</ref> NBC also asked for a premise pilot which told the story of how Laura Holt met the man who became Remington Steele. This second pilot, \"License to Steele\", became the first episode aired in the series.<ref>Michael Gleason audio commentary \"License to Steele,\" ''Remington Steele,'' season 1, disc 1 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005).</ref>\n\n[[Image:Remington Steele.jpg|left|thumb|250px|[[Pierce Brosnan]] and [[Stephanie Zimbalist]] in ''Remington Steele.'']]\n\n===Season 1===\nThe first season included two recurring characters: Murphy Michaels, a detective and rival for Laura's affections, played by [[James Read]]; and Bernice Foxe, the secretary-receptionist, played by Janet DeMay. Both Murphy and Bernice knew that Remington Steele was a fraud. Episodes in the first season set in motion the slow evolution of the romantic relationship between Laura and \"Mr. Steele\" (she never called him \"Remington\" until the show's fifth season after they were \"married\") while revealing elements of the characters' backstory. The first season established the pattern where each episode made direct reference to an old movie (for example, ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' and ''[[The Thomas Crown Affair (1968 film)|The Thomas Crown Affair]]'', which would be remade in 1999, with Pierce Brosnan in the lead role of Thomas Crown). Key episodes include \"Thou Shalt Not Steele\", which introduced Laura's mother and Felicia, a woman from Steele's past; \"Sting of Steele\", which introduced Daniel Chalmers ([[Efrem Zimbalist Jr.]], the real-life father of Stephanie) as Steele's former mentor; and \"Vintage Steele\", a fan favorite that focused on Laura's past.<ref>Susan Baskin, \"Vintage Steele: An Episode She'd Written Had Become Something of a Classic\", ''Los Angeles Times'', August 27, 2006.</ref> Additionally, writer Joel Steiger won an [[Edgar Award]] from the [[Mystery Writers of America]] for his script for the first-season episode \"In The Steele of the Night\".<ref>Mystery Writers of America, [http://www.mysterywriters.org/ Mysterywriters.org]</ref> ''Remington Steele'' also received strong critical reviews in the first season, noting its intelligence and stylish sophistication.<ref>John J. O'Connor, \"A Stylish Success\", ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1983.</ref>\n\n===Season 2===\nAt the end of season one, James Read made Michael Gleason aware that he was unhappy with the direction of his character.<ref>Michael Gleason, Doris Roberts audio commentary, \"Diced Steele\", ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 3, DVD.</ref> Gleason released him from the series and also let Janet DeMay go, thinking that the detective/investigator and secretary characters could be combined into one character. Gleason originally wrote the replacement character, Mildred Krebs, as an attractive 35-year-old woman who was a rival for Steele's affections. [[Doris Roberts]], an established character actress who had recently won an Emmy for a guest role on ''St. Elsewhere'', asked to read for the part. Although Roberts was not the right age for the character Gleason originally conceived, she won him over with her audition. Gleason then changed the character of Mildred Krebs to reflect the casting.<ref>Michael Gleason, Doris Roberts, \"Steele Mildred\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 2, DVD.</ref>\n\nNBC moved the series from Friday to Tuesday nights at 9pm following ''The A-Team'', increasing its budget and prominence on the network schedule. The second season continued the slow evolution of the relationship between Laura and Steele as he became a more competent detective. Key episodes include the two-hour season premiere, \"Steele Away With Me\", filmed on location in Mexico; \"Red Holt Steele\", a fan-favorite dramatic episode in which Laura's house is destroyed in an explosion; and \"Love Among the Steele\", another fan-favorite episode in which the agency acquires a 1936 [[Auburn Automobile|Auburn]] Boattail [[Auburn Speedster|Speedster]], which was used symbolically in several subsequent episodes.\n\n===Season 3===\n''Remington Steele'' achieved its greatest ratings success in the third season, finishing the year in the top 25.<ref>Richard Corliss, \"With class, smarts and luck, NBC has become the Cinderella network of '85\", ''Time Magazine'', March 4, 1985</ref> Key third-season episodes included the premiere, \"Steele At It\", shot on location in Cannes; \"Steele Your Heart Away\", shot on location in Ireland; and \"Maltese Steele\", shot on location in Malta. The season also included \"Steele Trying\", set in San Francisco and featuring the songs of [[Tony Bennett]], and \"Diced Steele\", filmed on location in Las Vegas. \"Puzzled Steele\" earned Doris Roberts an Emmy nomination for best supporting actress.<ref>\"Steele Trio\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 1, DVD</ref> The third season also included an episode, \"Steele in the Chips\", co-written by Stephanie Zimbalist and writing partner [[Robin Bernheim]].<ref>Stephanie Zimbalist, Robin Bernheim, and Michael Gleason, \"The Baking of Steele in the Chips\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 4, DVD.</ref> The final episode of the season ended with a cliffhanger as Laura and Steele seemed to be going their separate ways. Michael Gleason explained to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', \"We want to pull the relationship apart and bring it back together again with a little bit different attitude.\"<ref>Lee Margulies, \"Steele: He's Gone But Not Forgotten\", ''Los Angeles Times'' May 10, 1985</ref>\n\n===Season 4===\nSeason four was the final full season of the series. In the two-part season opener, \"Steele Searching\", filmed on location in London, Mildred Krebs learned of Steele's secret, changing the dynamics of the trio. Other key episodes, including \"Forged Steele\", \"Steele in the Spotlight\", and \"Sensitive Steele\", continued the slow evolution of the romantic relationship between the main characters. Facing a possible cancellation by NBC (whose fortunes had now changed to become the number-one network) Gleason contrived a phony marriage between the characters in the final episode of season four, \"Bonds of Steele\", as an attempt to garner additional interest and provoke NBC to pick up the series for a fifth season.<ref>Michael Gleason, Jeff Melvoin audio commentary, \"Bonds of Steele\", ''Remington Steele'' season 4, disc 4, DVD.</ref>\n\n===Proposals for season 5===\nGleason originally wanted the characters to have a real marriage at the end of season four and had plans for how to change the series in season five to accommodate the change, but both Brosnan and Zimbalist rejected the idea.<ref>Michael Gleason audio commentary, \"Diced Steele\", ''Remington Steele'' season 3, disc 3, DVD. See also Michael Gleason interview in ''Sound + Vision'', September 6, 2005, [http://www.soundandvisionmag.com/article/talking-tv-dvd-remington-steeles-michael-gleason?page=0,1 Soundandvisionmag.com]</ref> Following that decision, Gleason pitched another concept for season five to NBC in May 1986, introducing a character named \"Tony\" as a rival for Laura's affections.<ref>Michael Gleason papers in ''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 503-513.</ref>\n\n====Brief cancellation====\nThe series was cancelled at the end of the 1985&ndash;86 television season, although it still had a 28% share of the audience in its time slot. According to Michael Gleason, Brandon Tartikoff's decision to give an early pick-up to the [[Stephen J. Cannell]] series ''[[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|Hunter]]'' left no room on the NBC schedule for ''Remington Steele''.<ref>Michael Gleason audio commentary, \"Bonds of Steele\", ''Remington Steele'', season 4, disc 4, DVD.</ref> Two months after the cancellation, NBC executive [[Warren Littlefield]] reversed the decision, responding to an outpouring of support from fans and a sharp upswing in the show's ratings during the summer of 1986.<ref>Stephen Farber, \"'Remington Steele' Gets Reprieve\", ''The New York Times'', July 24, 1986</ref>\n\nThe cancellation and reversal affected film role opportunities for Brosnan and Zimbalist, as both had received firm offers to do films in the interim. [[Albert R. Broccoli|Albert R. \"Cubby\" Broccoli]] offered Brosnan the part of [[James Bond]] for the film ''[[The Living Daylights]]''. Following NBC's reversal, Broccoli stated he did not want Bond to be identified with a current TV series and instead gave the role to [[Timothy Dalton]].<ref>\"Take This Job & Shove it\", ''People Magazine'', August 11, 1986</ref> Brosnan became 007 in 1995, making his debut in the film ''[[GoldenEye|Goldeneye]]''.<ref>Kimberly Last, \"Pierce Brosnan's Long and Winding Road To Bond\", ''Goldeneye Magazine'', Spring 1996, [http://www.klast.net/bond/pb_road.html Klast.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061009210203/http://www.klast.net/bond/pb_road.html |date=2006-10-09 }}</ref> Zimbalist had accepted the role of Officer Anne Lewis in the science-fiction movie ''[[RoboCop]]'' and was forced to pull out of that production, to be replaced by [[Nancy Allen (actress)|Nancy Allen]].<ref>Alexandra Jacobs interview with Stephanie Zimbalist, \"Actress Roles Over 40? 'It's a Big Fat Zero'\", ''New York Observer'', November 24, 2003, [http://www.observer.com/node/48380 Observer.com]</ref>\n\n====Final season====\nNBC reversed the cancellation but did not slot a full twenty-two-episode season into their schedule. The final abbreviated season consisted of six hours of made-for-TV films broadcast in early 1987, including installments filmed on location in Mexico, London, and Ireland. [[Jack Scalia]] joined the cast as a rival for Laura's affections.<ref>Lee Margulies, \"'Remington Steele' To Return As Movie\", ''Los Angeles Times'', December 10, 1986</ref> The circumstances surrounding Steele's birth as well as the identity of Steele's father are revealed in the final episode. The final scene of the series implied that Steele and Laura were about to consummate their relationship.<ref>Lee Margulies, \"Love Will Find A Way On 'Remington Steele'\", ''Los Angeles Times'', August 29, 1986</ref>\n\n===Rumors of discord===\nAlthough part of the show's appeal was the sexual tension between the main characters, in real life the production was dogged for years by rumors that its two leads did not get along. Brosnan and Zimbalist have admitted some level of personal conflict in press interviews during and since, attributing some of it to the stress of long working hours, while also maintaining that it did not damage their ability to work together.<ref>David Wallace, \"Stephanie Zimbalist Interview\", ''People Magazine'', January 14, 1985.</ref> Doris Roberts confirmed that Zimbalist and Brosnan rarely spoke to each other and that such tension played a role in the series' end. \"It was awful. They didn't talk to each other.\"<ref>Doris Roberts interview, Chapter 7, Archives of American Television, 2005 [https://interviews.televisionacademy.com/interviews/doris-roberts Emmytvlegends.org]</ref> Whatever discord there may have been at the time of production, Brosnan and Zimbalist speak fondly of one another in more recent interviews and are occasionally in touch.<ref>See Cheryl Johnson, \"Stephanie Zimbalist gets her Weather Wish\", ''Minneapolis Star Tribune'', April 25, 2000, for an account of a 1999 reunion between Brosnan and Zimbalist.</ref> In an interview included on the DVD release of Season 1, Brosnan says they did get along and trusted one another professionally.<ref>Pierce Brosnan in \"Remington and Laura\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 1, disc 2, DVD.</ref> Brosnan also praises Zimbalist's acting on his official web site, saying that he would work with her again on the right project.<ref name=\"Brosnandotcom\"/> Zimbalist returned the compliment in a 2011 interview with the ''New Jersey Star-Ledger'', saying \"Pierce Brosnan is a very sweet man.\"<ref>Peter Filichia interview with Stephanie Zimbalist, \"The Subject Was Roses' preview: Dark 1960s drama is revived at George Street\", ''New Jersey Star-Ledger'', February 4, 2011, [http://www.nj.com/entertainment/arts/index.ssf/2011/02/the_subject_was_roses_preview.html Nj.com]</ref>\n\n===Reboot projects===\nFilm: With the release of the series on DVD in 2005, Pierce Brosnan expressed interest in developing a ''Remington Steele'' feature film through his production company, Irish Dream Time,<ref>Rebecca Murray, \"Pierce Brosnan Discusses 'The Matador' and his Upcoming Films,\" [http://movies.about.com/od/thematador/a/matadorpb122605_2.htm About.com]</ref> but later stated on his web site that it is unlikely to be produced.<ref name=\"Brosnandotcom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.piercebrosnan.com/menu.php?mm=8&sm=17&pn=2|title=Previous Q&A Questions|publisher=PierceBrosnan.com|accessdate=2007-04-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928072146/http://www.piercebrosnan.com/menu.php?mm=8&sm=17&pn=2|archivedate=2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\nTelevision: In October 2013 NBC announced plans to reboot the series as a half-hour comedy.<ref>Jessica Gelt, \"Remington Steele gets Reboot as a Comedy Courtesy NBC\", ''Los Angeles Times'', October 9, 2013, [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-remington-steele-reboot-comedy-nbc-20131009,0,5404250.story Los Angeles Times]</ref> NBC's deal with 20th Century Fox had screenwriters and a director attached but no cast was attached {{as of|2013|lc=yes}}.<ref>Nellie Adreeva, \"NBC to Reboot Remington Steele as a Comedy\", ''Deadline Hollywood'', October 9, 2013, [http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/remington-steele-reboot-nbc/ Deadline.com]</ref>\n\n==Home releases==\n[[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment|20th Century Fox]] has released all five seasons of ''Remington Steele'' on DVD in Region 1 in four box sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Remington-Steele/3518|title=Remington Steele|website=[[TVShowsOnDVD.com]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304215448/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Remington-Steele/3518|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> The Season 1 DVD inadvertently echoed an ongoing joke in the series in that Stephanie Zimbalist, who had top billing when the show was on the air, was initially omitted from all promotional material connected with its release, as well as the DVD box itself, as Fox Video chose to promote Pierce Brosnan as the sole star. Subsequently, a sticker saying \"Also starring Stephanie Zimbalist\" was added to the packaging as an afterthought. This omission was corrected with the release of the second season which gave Zimbalist star billing with her photograph appearing on the box. Additionally, Zimbalist is featured on the behind-the-scenes featurettes contained therein. The first-season boxed set also has a picture of Doris Roberts on the back cover, even though she didn't join the show until the second season.\n\nSeason 1 has also been released in Region 2 & 4.\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n! DVD set\n! Episodes\n! Release date\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Season One''\n| 22\n| {{date|2005-7-26|mdy}}\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Season Two''\n| 22\n| {{date|2005-11-8|mdy}}\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Season Three''\n| 22\n| {{date|2006-4-18|mdy}}\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Seasons Four & Five''\n| 28\n| {{date|2006-8-15|mdy}}\n|}\n\n==Syndication==\nAfter a nearly two-decade absence from local syndication, the series returned to broadcast television and was seen from September 3 to December 31, 2012, on [[MeTV]] and resumed in September 2013. It is also currently{{when|date=March 2019}} airing on Family Net. Reruns have previously aired on [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] from 1995 to 1997 and on PAX (now [[Ion Television]]) from 2000 to 2001. It also aired in India on [[Star Plus]] in early 1990s to March 31, 1993.\n\nMeTV ran the series starting 29 May 2017 in place of ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'', beginning with the season 2 premiere, \"Steele Away with Me\". ''Diagnosis: Murde''r returned on 21 August 2017.\n\nIn The UK, Freeview Channel 5USA, started showing the series from the first episode on October 30, 2017.\n\n==Production notes==\n* Every episode title has the word \"Steele\" in it.\n* At the end of every episode, [[MTM Enterprises#Mimsie the Cat|the MTM kitten Mimsie]] has an animated [[deerstalker]]'s cap on its head and a [[meerschaum pipe]] in its mouth, \u00e0 la [[Sherlock Holmes]]. The pipe falls from the kitten's mouth and bounces twice on the bottom of the screen as the kitten meows.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|0083470}}\n*{{tv.com show|remington-steele|Remington Steele}}\n*[http://steeleinlove.com/index2.html Remington Steele episode transcripts]\n\n{{MTM Enterprises}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Television|United States}}\n\n[[Category:1982 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1987 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American mystery television series]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American detective television series]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:Fictional detective agencies]]\n[[Category:Fictional detectives]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television series by MTM Enterprises]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Remington Steele\n| image = Remington Steele logo black.svg\n| genre = {{unbulleted list|[[Comedy-drama]]|[[Police procedural|Detective procedural]]|[[Action fiction|Action]]/[[Adventure fiction|adventure]]|[[Crime fiction]]|[[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]|Romance}}\n| camera =\n| runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials) \n| creator = [[Robert Butler (director)|Robert Butler]]<br />Michael Gleason\n| developer = \n| producer = Kevin Inch<br />Gareth Davies<br />Richard DeRoy\n| executive_producer = Michael Gleason\n| presenter = [[MTM Enterprises]]\n| starring = [[Stephanie Zimbalist]]<br />[[Pierce Brosnan]]<br />[[Doris Roberts]]\n| narrated = [[Stephanie Zimbalist]] in character as Laura Holt (Season 1 titles only)\n| theme_music_composer = [[Henry Mancini]]; incidental music by Richard Lewis Warren\n| opentheme = \"The ''Remington Steele'' Theme\", composed by Henry Mancini\n| endtheme = \"Laura Holt's Tune\", composed by Henry Mancini\n| company = [[MTM Enterprises]]\n| distributor = [[MTM Enterprises|MTM Television Distribution Group]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| location = [[Los Angeles]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| network = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format = Color\n| audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|1982|10|1}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|1987|2|17}}\n| num_seasons = 5\n| num_episodes = 94\n| list_episodes = List of Remington Steele episodes \n}}\n\n'''''Remington Steele''''' is an American [[police procedural]] [[crime drama]] television series co-created by [[Robert Butler (director)|Robert Butler]] and Michael Gleason. The series, starring [[Stephanie Zimbalist]] and [[Pierce Brosnan]], was produced by [[MTM Enterprises]] and first broadcast on the [[NBC]] network from October 10, [[1982 in television|1982]] to February 17, [[1987 in television|1987]]. The series blended the genres of romantic comedy, drama, detective procedural and (towards the end of the series) international political intrigue and espionage.\n\n''Remington Steele's'' premise is that Laura Holt, a licensed [[private investigator]] played by Stephanie Zimbalist, opened a detective agency under her own name but found potential clients refused to hire a woman, no matter how qualified. To solve the problem, Laura invents a fictitious male superior she names Remington Steele. Through a series of events in the first episode, \"License to Steele\", Pierce Brosnan's character, a former thief and con man (whose real name even ''he'' proves not to know and is never revealed), assumes the identity of Remington Steele. Behind the scenes, a power struggle ensues between Laura and Steele as to who is really in charge, while the two carry on a casual romantic relationship.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Stephanie Zimbalist]] as Laura Holt\n*[[Pierce Brosnan]] as Special Agent Ben Pearson/Remington Steele\n*[[Doris Roberts]] as Mildred Krebs (from Season 2 onward) \n*[[Janet DeMay]] as Bernice Foxe (Season 1)\n*[[James Read]] as Murphy Michaels (Season 1)\n*[[Jack Scalia]] as Tony Roselli (Season 5)\nOther recurring actors included: \n*[[Cassandra Harris]] (late wife of Pierce Brosnan) as Felicia, one of Steele's old flames (3 episodes), and Anna, a mysterious woman from Steele's past (1 episode)\n*[[Efrem Zimbalist Jr.]] as Daniel Chalmers, a charming con man who was Steele's mentor and later revealed to be his biological father\n*[[Beverly Garland]] as Abigail Holt, Laura's mother\n*[[Gary Frank (actor)|Gary Frank]] as Detective James Jarvis, a less-than-competent police detective who more often than not falsely accused the principal characters and their clients of murder\n*[[Michael Constantine]] as George Edward Mulch, a businessman with far-fetched ideas looking only for fame and fortune\n*[[James Tolkan]] as Norman Keyes, an insurance investigator bent on proving Steele to be a fraud\n*[[Blake Clark]] as Fred, the Chauffeur\nGuest stars included:\n*[[Louie Anderson]], \"Steele Spawning\", Season 4\n*[[Tom Baker]] \"Hounded Steele\" Season 2\n*[[Judith Barsi]], \"Suburban Steele\", Season 4\n*[[Thom Bray]], \"Signed, Steeled and Delivered\", Season 1\n*[[Delta Burke]], \"Altared Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Daniel Davis]], \"Gourmet Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Geena Davis]], \"Steele in the Chips\", Season 3\n*[[Sarah Douglas (actress)|Sarah Douglas]], \"Steele Hanging In There\", Season 5\n*[[Whitey Ford]] and [[Mickey Mantle]], \"Second Base Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Conrad Janis]], \"Stronger Than Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Jeffrey Jones]], \"A Steele at Any Price\", Season 2\n*[[Jane Kaczmarek]], \"Altared Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Dorothy Lamour]], \"Cast in Steele\", Season 3\n*[[John Larroquette]], \"Breath of Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Judith Light]], \"Dreams of Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Rose Marie]], \"Steele in the Spotlight\", Season 4\n*[[A Martinez]], \"High Flying Steele\", Season 2\n*[[Virginia Mayo]], \"Cast of Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Beverlee McKinsey]], \"Vintage Steele\", Season 1\n*[[Lloyd Nolan]], \"Cast in Steele\", Season 3\n*[[Annie Potts]], \"Steele Crazy After All These Years\", Season 1\n*[[Faith Prince]], \"Scene Steelers\", Season 2\n*[[Ford Rainey]], \u201dSmall Town Steele\u201d, Season 2\n*[[Paul Reiser]], \"A Good Night's Steele\", Season 1\n*[[Peter Scolari]], \"Steele Waters Run Deep\", Season 1\n*[[Jean Smart]], \"Steele in the Chips\", Season 3\n*[[Sharon Stone]], \"Steele Crazy After All These Years\", Season 1\n*[[John van Dreelen]], \u201dSteele Threads, Season 2\n*[[Barry Van Dyke]], \"Steele Belted\", Season 1\n*[[Guy Boyd]], \"Hearts of Steele\", \"Steele Framed\", \"Elegy of Steele\", Season 1 & 2\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Remington Steele episodes}}\n{{:List of Remington Steele episodes}}\n\n==Significance and influence==\n''Remington Steele'' is best known for having launched the career of [[Pierce Brosnan]]<ref>Mark Murphy and Frank Swertlow, \"Why Would I Do a Poster? Would Robert De Niro?\", ''TV Guide'', June 9, 1984</ref> and for serving as a forerunner of the similar, edgier series ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]],''<ref>Robert J. Thompson, ''Television's Second Golden Age'' (New York: Continuum, 1996) 112-113.</ref> and was also an influential part of television history in its own right. Recent evaluations, in the wake of the show's full release on DVD, conclude that ''Steele'' was solidly crafted, well-acted and groundbreaking in its own way.<ref>Emily VanDerWerff, \"Primer: 1980s Television Dramas\", page 2, \"In the Genre Trenches\", A.V. Club, April 28, 2011 [http://www.avclub.com/articles/1980s-tv-dramas,55221/2/ The A.V. Club]; see also Cory Barker, \"Test Pilot: File #20 Remington Steele\", TV Surveillance blog, August 3, 2011, [http://tvsurveillance.com/2011/08/03/test-pilot-file-20-remington-steele/ Tvsurveillance.com]</ref> Other recent evaluations have also noted that series has aged better than some other series of its time and genre.<ref>Lucy Mangan, \"Cable Girl\", ''The Guardian'' (U.K.), August 11, 2008, [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/aug/12/television2 The Guardian]</ref>\n\n===Innovations===\n''Remington Steele'' referenced [[film noir]] in the mystery storylines.<ref>Michael Gleason, \"Comedy and Old Movies\" special feature ''Remington Steele,'' season 1, disc 3 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005), DVD</ref> It subverted 1970s detective show conventions by telling its stories from the point of view of an independent, professional woman.<ref>Michael Ryan, Sound on Sight magazine, October 26, 2011, [http://www.soundonsight.org/obsessive-compulsive-procedural-2-prime-suspect/ Soundonsight.org]</ref> At a time when hour-long series were serious and half-hour series were humorous, ''Steele'' incorporated multiple styles of comedy into the standard detective format.<ref>Michael Gleason and Jeff Melvoin audio commentary, \"Diced Steele\", ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 3 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2006), DVD</ref> It pioneered the slowly evolving \"will they or won't they\" relationship arc that is now common to television drama of all genres.<ref>Noel Holston, \"Sexual Tension Teases Stars and Viewers,\" ''Orlando Sentinel'', February 9, 1986, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-02-09/entertainment/8601100825_1_remington-steele-angela-bower-pierce-brosnan Chicago Tribune]</ref><ref>Kate Aurthur, \"Do It Already,\" Slate.com, April 3, 2006, [http://www.slate.com/id/2139176/ Slate]</ref>\n\n===Laura Holt as role model===\nIn an interview recorded in 2005 for a DVD special feature, ''Remington Steele'' co-creator Michael Gleason and star Stephanie Zimbalist discuss the large number of women who have approached them over the years to express their appreciation for the character of Laura Holt. Speaking of the women she meets, Zimbalist said \"They are extraordinary women.... They are interesting. They do interesting things. They are smart. They're independent. They're sort of, what my character was \u2013 and I meet them all the time.\"<ref>Michael Gleason and Stephanie Zimbalist in \"Steele Together\", ''Remington Steele'', season 2, disc 3 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005), DVD, 5:52 \u2013 7:12.</ref> Also in 2005, Robin Rauzi published an article in the ''Los Angeles Times'' saying that Laura Holt was her hero.<ref>Robin Rauzi, \"Following in Her Fedora; A Laura Holt Fan Goes on Location, Sort of, With Her Hero\", ''Los Angeles Times'', September 8, 2005.</ref> In a subsequent interview Rauzi elaborated, saying that Laura \"was one of the only examples of an unmarried modern career woman on TV that I could identify with at that time\" and that Laura \"didn\u2019t seem that far away from who I was and who I could be.\" Rauzi concludes, \"I\u2019ve decided to stop being embarrassed to say ''Remington Steele'' changed my life. It did and for the better.\"<ref>Robin Rauzi in \"Steele Fanatics\", ''Remington Steele'', season 4, disc 1 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2006), DVD, 3:15 \u2013 4:20.</ref>\n\n==Series history==\n\n===Development===\n''Remington Steele\u2019s'' initial premise was conceived in 1969 by long-time television director [[Robert Butler (director)|Robert Butler]]<ref>Robert Butler interview, chapter 7, Archive of American Television, January 14, 2004, [http://emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/robert-butler/ Emmytvlegends.org]</ref> as a series featuring a solo female private investigator. Butler pitched the idea to [[Grant Tinker]] before he was head of [[MTM Enterprises|MTM]], but Tinker felt the series was ahead of its time. In January 1980, following the success of several sitcoms featuring working women, including the groundbreaking ''Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' Butler and Tinker, now head of MTM, revived the concept.<ref>''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 23, 43.</ref> MTM Vice President of Programming Stu Erwin felt Butler's concept was only \"half a show\" and suggested that Butler work with veteran writer Michael Gleason<ref>Michael Gleason [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0322327/ IMDb]</ref> to expand the premise. Imagining Holt's fictional boss, Gleason proposed to Butler, \u201cWouldn\u2019t it be great if he showed up and made her crazy?\u201d<ref>Robert Butler, Stu Erwin, and Michael Gleason, \u201cMaking of Remington Steele Season One,\u201d ''Remington Steele'', season 1, disc 1 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005), DVD, 0:17 \u2013 1:52.</ref> In 1981, Gleason, Butler, Erwin and Tinker pitched the series to NBC and were initially rejected by executives who failed to \"get\" the premise. Shortly thereafter, Tinker left MTM to become chairman of NBC, then the number-three network, and subsequently a pilot was ordered.<ref>Michael Gleason, \"Foreword\" in ''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 16-17.</ref>\n\nStephanie Zimbalist, an established actress with roles in several television movies, was approached for the role of Laura Holt. At first she turned the series down, not wishing to be tied down to one show, but had a late-night change of heart.<ref>Michael Leahy, \"The Time: 5:30 A.M., Her Thought: 'I must be an Idiot'\", ''[[TV Guide]]'', November 20, 1982.</ref> Pierce Brosnan (best known then for his role in ''[[Manions of America|The Manions of America]]'') auditioned for the role of Remington Steele but was initially refused by NBC executives who were concerned that Brosnan was a relative unknown in America. MTM's Stu Erwin stood firm in a face-to-face meeting with NBC executive [[Brandon Tartikoff]] and Tartikoff relented.<ref>''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 28.</ref>\n\nOriginally, NBC asked for a pilot that imagined the series six months into its run, with the characters already working together in the detective agency. This pilot was produced in February and March 1982 and was eventually aired with revisions as \"Tempered Steele\". NBC had some concerns about audience confusion over this episode, but ultimately agreed to schedule the series for the 1982-83 season.<ref>''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective,'' Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 29-30.</ref> NBC also asked for a premise pilot which told the story of how Laura Holt met the man who became Remington Steele. This second pilot, \"License to Steele\", became the first episode aired in the series.<ref>Michael Gleason audio commentary \"License to Steele,\" ''Remington Steele,'' season 1, disc 1 (Beverly Hills: 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment, 2005).</ref>\n\n[[Image:Remington Steele.jpg|left|thumb|250px|[[Pierce Brosnan]] and [[Stephanie Zimbalist]] in ''Remington Steele.'']]\n\n===Season 1===\nThe first season included two recurring characters: Murphy Michaels, a detective and rival for Laura's affections, played by [[James Read]]; and Bernice Foxe, the secretary-receptionist, played by Janet DeMay. Both Murphy and Bernice knew that Remington Steele was a fraud. Episodes in the first season set in motion the slow evolution of the romantic relationship between Laura and \"Mr. Steele\" (she never called him \"Remington\" until the show's fifth season after they were \"married\") while revealing elements of the characters' backstory. The first season established the pattern where each episode made direct reference to an old movie (for example, ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' and ''[[The Thomas Crown Affair (1968 film)|The Thomas Crown Affair]]'', which would be remade in 1999, with Pierce Brosnan in the lead role of Thomas Crown). Key episodes include \"Thou Shalt Not Steele\", which introduced Laura's mother and Felicia, a woman from Steele's past; \"Sting of Steele\", which introduced Daniel Chalmers ([[Efrem Zimbalist Jr.]], the real-life father of Stephanie) as Steele's former mentor; and \"Vintage Steele\", a fan favorite that focused on Laura's past.<ref>Susan Baskin, \"Vintage Steele: An Episode She'd Written Had Become Something of a Classic\", ''Los Angeles Times'', August 27, 2006.</ref> Additionally, writer Joel Steiger won an [[Edgar Award]] from the [[Mystery Writers of America]] for his script for the first-season episode \"In The Steele of the Night\".<ref>Mystery Writers of America, [http://www.mysterywriters.org/ Mysterywriters.org]</ref> ''Remington Steele'' also received strong critical reviews in the first season, noting its intelligence and stylish sophistication.<ref>John J. O'Connor, \"A Stylish Success\", ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1983.</ref>\n\n===Season 2===\nAt the end of season one, James Read made Michael Gleason aware that he was unhappy with the direction of his character.<ref>Michael Gleason, Doris Roberts audio commentary, \"Diced Steele\", ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 3, DVD.</ref> Gleason released him from the series and also let Janet DeMay go, thinking that the detective/investigator and secretary characters could be combined into one character. Gleason originally wrote the replacement character, Mildred Krebs, as an attractive 35-year-old woman who was a rival for Steele's affections. [[Doris Roberts]], an established character actress who had recently won an Emmy for a guest role on ''St. Elsewhere'', asked to read for the part. Although Roberts was not the right age for the character Gleason originally conceived, she won him over with her audition. Gleason then changed the character of Mildred Krebs to reflect the casting.<ref>Michael Gleason, Doris Roberts, \"Steele Mildred\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 2, DVD.</ref>\n\nNBC moved the series from Friday to Tuesday nights at 9pm following ''The A-Team'', increasing its budget and prominence on the network schedule. The second season continued the slow evolution of the relationship between Laura and Steele as he became a more competent detective. Key episodes include the two-hour season premiere, \"Steele Away With Me\", filmed on location in Mexico; \"Red Holt Steele\", a fan-favorite dramatic episode in which Laura's house is destroyed in an explosion; and \"Love Among the Steele\", another fan-favorite episode in which the agency acquires a 1936 [[Auburn Automobile|Auburn]] Boattail [[Auburn Speedster|Speedster]], which was used symbolically in several subsequent episodes.\n\n===Season 3===\n''Remington Steele'' achieved its greatest ratings success in the third season, finishing the year in the top 25.<ref>Richard Corliss, \"With class, smarts and luck, NBC has become the Cinderella network of '85\", ''Time Magazine'', March 4, 1985</ref> Key third-season episodes included the premiere, \"Steele At It\", shot on location in Cannes; \"Steele Your Heart Away\", shot on location in Ireland; and \"Maltese Steele\", shot on location in Malta. The season also included \"Steele Trying\", set in San Francisco and featuring the songs of [[Tony Bennett]], and \"Diced Steele\", filmed on location in Las Vegas. \"Puzzled Steele\" earned Doris Roberts an Emmy nomination for best supporting actress.<ref>\"Steele Trio\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 1, DVD</ref> The third season also included an episode, \"Steele in the Chips\", co-written by Stephanie Zimbalist and writing partner [[Robin Bernheim]].<ref>Stephanie Zimbalist, Robin Bernheim, and Michael Gleason, \"The Baking of Steele in the Chips\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 3, disc 4, DVD.</ref> The final episode of the season ended with a cliffhanger as Laura and Steele seemed to be going their separate ways. Michael Gleason explained to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', \"We want to pull the relationship apart and bring it back together again with a little bit different attitude.\"<ref>Lee Margulies, \"Steele: He's Gone But Not Forgotten\", ''Los Angeles Times'' May 10, 1985</ref>\n\n===Season 4===\nSeason four was the final full season of the series. In the two-part season opener, \"Steele Searching\", filmed on location in London, Mildred Krebs learned of Steele's secret, changing the dynamics of the trio. Other key episodes, including \"Forged Steele\", \"Steele in the Spotlight\", and \"Sensitive Steele\", continued the slow evolution of the romantic relationship between the main characters. Facing a possible cancellation by NBC (whose fortunes had now changed to become the number-one network) Gleason contrived a phony marriage between the characters in the final episode of season four, \"Bonds of Steele\", as an attempt to garner additional interest and provoke NBC to pick up the series for a fifth season.<ref>Michael Gleason, Jeff Melvoin audio commentary, \"Bonds of Steele\", ''Remington Steele'' season 4, disc 4, DVD.</ref>\n\n===Proposals for season 5===\nGleason originally wanted the characters to have a real marriage at the end of season four and had plans for how to change the series in season five to accommodate the change, but both Brosnan and Zimbalist rejected the idea.<ref>Michael Gleason audio commentary, \"Diced Steele\", ''Remington Steele'' season 3, disc 3, DVD. See also Michael Gleason interview in ''Sound + Vision'', September 6, 2005, [http://www.soundandvisionmag.com/article/talking-tv-dvd-remington-steeles-michael-gleason?page=0,1 Soundandvisionmag.com]</ref> Following that decision, Gleason pitched another concept for season five to NBC in May 1986, introducing a character named \"Tony\" as a rival for Laura's affections.<ref>Michael Gleason papers in ''Steele Loved After All These Years: A Remington Steele Retrospective'', Judith A. Moose (Bear Manor Media, 2007) 503-513.</ref>\n\n====Brief cancellation====\nThe series was cancelled at the end of the 1985&ndash;86 television season, although it still had a 28% share of the audience in its time slot. According to Michael Gleason, Brandon Tartikoff's decision to give an early pick-up to the [[Stephen J. Cannell]] series ''[[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|Hunter]]'' left no room on the NBC schedule for ''Remington Steele''.<ref>Michael Gleason audio commentary, \"Bonds of Steele\", ''Remington Steele'', season 4, disc 4, DVD.</ref> Two months after the cancellation, NBC executive [[Warren Littlefield]] reversed the decision, responding to an outpouring of support from fans and a sharp upswing in the show's ratings during the summer of 1986.<ref>Stephen Farber, \"'Remington Steele' Gets Reprieve\", ''The New York Times'', July 24, 1986</ref>\n\nThe cancellation and reversal affected film role opportunities for Brosnan and Zimbalist, as both had received firm offers to do films in the interim. [[Albert R. Broccoli|Albert R. \"Cubby\" Broccoli]] offered Brosnan the part of [[James Bond]] for the film ''[[The Living Daylights]]''. Following NBC's reversal, Broccoli stated he did not want Bond to be identified with a current TV series and instead gave the role to [[Timothy Dalton]].<ref>\"Take This Job & Shove it\", ''People Magazine'', August 11, 1986</ref> Brosnan became 007 in 1995, making his debut in the film ''[[GoldenEye|Goldeneye]]''.<ref>Kimberly Last, \"Pierce Brosnan's Long and Winding Road To Bond\", ''Goldeneye Magazine'', Spring 1996, [http://www.klast.net/bond/pb_road.html Klast.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061009210203/http://www.klast.net/bond/pb_road.html |date=2006-10-09 }}</ref> Zimbalist had accepted the role of Officer Anne Lewis in the science-fiction movie ''[[RoboCop]]'' and was forced to pull out of that production, to be replaced by [[Nancy Allen (actress)|Nancy Allen]].<ref>Alexandra Jacobs interview with Stephanie Zimbalist, \"Actress Roles Over 40? 'It's a Big Fat Zero'\", ''New York Observer'', November 24, 2003, [http://www.observer.com/node/48380 Observer.com]</ref>\n\n====Final season====\nNBC reversed the cancellation but did not slot a full twenty-two-episode season into their schedule. The final abbreviated season consisted of six hours of made-for-TV films broadcast in early 1987, including installments filmed on location in Mexico, London, and Ireland. [[Jack Scalia]] joined the cast as a rival for Laura's affections.<ref>Lee Margulies, \"'Remington Steele' To Return As Movie\", ''Los Angeles Times'', December 10, 1986</ref> The circumstances surrounding Steele's birth as well as the identity of Steele's father are revealed in the final episode. The final scene of the series implied that Steele and Laura were about to consummate their relationship.<ref>Lee Margulies, \"Love Will Find A Way On 'Remington Steele'\", ''Los Angeles Times'', August 29, 1986</ref>\n\n===Rumors of discord===\nAlthough part of the show's appeal was the sexual tension between the main characters, in real life the production was dogged for years by rumors that its two leads did not get along. Brosnan and Zimbalist have admitted some level of personal conflict in press interviews during and since, attributing some of it to the stress of long working hours, while also maintaining that it did not damage their ability to work together.<ref>David Wallace, \"Stephanie Zimbalist Interview\", ''People Magazine'', January 14, 1985.</ref> Doris Roberts confirmed that Zimbalist and Brosnan rarely spoke to each other and that such tension played a role in the series' end. \"It was awful. They didn't talk to each other.\"<ref>Doris Roberts interview, Chapter 7, Archives of American Television, 2005 [https://interviews.televisionacademy.com/interviews/doris-roberts Emmytvlegends.org]</ref> Whatever discord there may have been at the time of production, Brosnan and Zimbalist speak fondly of one another in more recent interviews and are occasionally in touch.<ref>See Cheryl Johnson, \"Stephanie Zimbalist gets her Weather Wish\", ''Minneapolis Star Tribune'', April 25, 2000, for an account of a 1999 reunion between Brosnan and Zimbalist.</ref> In an interview included on the DVD release of Season 1, Brosnan says they did get along and trusted one another professionally.<ref>Pierce Brosnan in \"Remington and Laura\" special feature, ''Remington Steele'', season 1, disc 2, DVD.</ref> Brosnan also praises Zimbalist's acting on his official web site, saying that he would work with her again on the right project.<ref name=\"Brosnandotcom\"/> Zimbalist returned the compliment in a 2011 interview with the ''New Jersey Star-Ledger'', saying \"Pierce Brosnan is a very sweet man.\"<ref>Peter Filichia interview with Stephanie Zimbalist, \"The Subject Was Roses' preview: Dark 1960s drama is revived at George Street\", ''New Jersey Star-Ledger'', February 4, 2011, [http://www.nj.com/entertainment/arts/index.ssf/2011/02/the_subject_was_roses_preview.html Nj.com]</ref>\n\n===Reboot projects===\nFilm: With the release of the series on DVD in 2005, Pierce Brosnan expressed interest in developing a ''Remington Steele'' feature film through his production company, Irish Dream Time,<ref>Rebecca Murray, \"Pierce Brosnan Discusses 'The Matador' and his Upcoming Films,\" [http://movies.about.com/od/thematador/a/matadorpb122605_2.htm About.com]</ref> but later stated on his web site that it is unlikely to be produced.<ref name=\"Brosnandotcom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.piercebrosnan.com/menu.php?mm=8&sm=17&pn=2|title=Previous Q&A Questions|publisher=PierceBrosnan.com|accessdate=2007-04-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928072146/http://www.piercebrosnan.com/menu.php?mm=8&sm=17&pn=2|archivedate=2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\nTelevision: In October 2013 NBC announced plans to reboot the series as a half-hour comedy.<ref>Jessica Gelt, \"Remington Steele gets Reboot as a Comedy Courtesy NBC\", ''Los Angeles Times'', October 9, 2013, [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-remington-steele-reboot-comedy-nbc-20131009,0,5404250.story Los Angeles Times]</ref> NBC's deal with 20th Century Fox had screenwriters and a director attached but no cast was attached {{as of|2013|lc=yes}}.<ref>Nellie Adreeva, \"NBC to Reboot Remington Steele as a Comedy\", ''Deadline Hollywood'', October 9, 2013, [http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/remington-steele-reboot-nbc/ Deadline.com]</ref>\n\n==Home releases==\n[[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment|20th Century Fox]] has released all five seasons of ''Remington Steele'' on DVD in Region 1 in four box sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Remington-Steele/3518|title=Remington Steele|website=[[TVShowsOnDVD.com]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304215448/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Remington-Steele/3518|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> The Season 1 DVD inadvertently echoed an ongoing joke in the series in that Stephanie Zimbalist, who had top billing when the show was on the air, was initially omitted from all promotional material connected with its release, as well as the DVD box itself, as Fox Video chose to promote Pierce Brosnan as the sole star. Subsequently, a sticker saying \"Also starring Stephanie Zimbalist\" was added to the packaging as an afterthought. This omission was corrected with the release of the second season which gave Zimbalist star billing with her photograph appearing on the box. Additionally, Zimbalist is featured on the behind-the-scenes featurettes contained therein. The first-season boxed set also has a picture of Doris Roberts on the back cover, even though she didn't join the show until the second season.\n\nSeason 1 has also been released in Region 2 & 4.\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n! DVD set\n! Episodes\n! Release date\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Season One''\n| 22\n| {{date|2005-7-26|mdy}}\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Season Two''\n| 22\n| {{date|2005-11-8|mdy}}\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Season Three''\n| 22\n| {{date|2006-4-18|mdy}}\n|-\n| ''Remington Steele: Seasons Four & Five''\n| 28\n| {{date|2006-8-15|mdy}}\n|}\n\n==Syndication==\nAfter a nearly two-decade absence from local syndication, the series returned to broadcast television and was seen from September 3 to December 31, 2012, on [[MeTV]] and resumed in September 2013. It is also currently{{when|date=March 2019}} airing on Family Net. Reruns have previously aired on [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] from 1995 to 1997 and on PAX (now [[Ion Television]]) from 2000 to 2001. It also aired in India on [[Star Plus]] in early 1990s to March 31, 1993.\n\nMeTV ran the series starting 29 May 2017 in place of ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'', beginning with the season 2 premiere, \"Steele Away with Me\". ''Diagnosis: Murde''r returned on 21 August 2017.\n\nIn The UK, Freeview Channel 5USA, started showing the series from the first episode on October 30, 2017.\n\n==Production notes==\n* Every episode title has the word \"Steele\" in it.\n* At the end of every episode, [[MTM Enterprises#Mimsie the Cat|the MTM kitten Mimsie]] has an animated [[deerstalker]]'s cap on its head and a [[meerschaum pipe]] in its mouth, \u00e0 la [[Sherlock Holmes]]. The pipe falls from the kitten's mouth and bounces twice on the bottom of the screen as the kitten meows.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|0083470}}\n*{{tv.com show|remington-steele|Remington Steele}}\n*[http://steeleinlove.com/index2.html Remington Steele episode transcripts]\n\n{{MTM Enterprises}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Television|United States}}\n\n[[Category:1982 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1987 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American mystery television series]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American detective television series]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:Fictional detective agencies]]\n[[Category:Fictional detectives]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television series by MTM Enterprises]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGuy Boyd(link changed toGuy Boyd (actor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remington_Steele"}
{"title_page": "Gokula Krishnan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image       =\n|imagesize   =\n|caption     = \n|name        = Gokula Krishnan\n|birth_date   = 1945\n|birth_place = [[Tirunelveli]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n|birth_name   = \n|death_date  = {{Death date|df=yes|2008|10|28}} (aged 63)\n|death_place = [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n|other_name(s)= \n|occupation  = Film director\n|spouse = Kavitha\n|yearsactive = 1982\u20132008\n|website    = \n|\n}}\n\n'''Gokula Krishnan''' was an [[India]]n film director, who has directed Tamil films. He was primarily active in the 1980s and early 1990s and is most noted for his work on films featuring actor [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]. He also extensively worked with Malayalam director [[Fazil (director)|Fazil]], when he made Tamil films, helping write dialogues.<ref>http://www.indiaglitz.com/director-gokulakrishna-passes-away-tamil-news-42616.html</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGokula Krishnan made his directorial debut in the early 1980s, before choosing to prioritise his work as a script-writer to Malayalam director [[Fazil (director)|Fazil]], when he made Tamil films. In the mid 1990s, Gokula Krishnan made three consecutive films with actor [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]. ''[[Muthu Kaalai]]'' (1995), ''[[Poovarasan]]'' (1996) and ''[[Udhavikku Varalaamaa]]'' (1998) all fared poorly at the box office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Specials/97/Oct/a-z/atoz-5.htm |title=A-Z (V) |work=Indolink Tamil |accessdate=2012-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424003725/http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Specials/97/Oct/a-z/atoz-5.htm |archivedate=24 April 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHe died after a brief illness on 28 October 2008, leaving behind his wife, Kavitha.<ref>http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/oct-08-05/gokula-krishnan-29-10-08.html</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===As director===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-  style=\"background:#cccccf; text-align:center;\"\n| '''Year''' || '''Film''' || '''Notes'''\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Archanai Pookal]]'' ||\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Aanandha Kummi]]'' ||\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Maragatha Veenai]]'' ||\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Muthu Kaalai]]'' ||\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Poovarasan]]'' ||\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Udhavikku Varalaamaa]]'' ||\n|}\n\n===As writer only===\n*''[[Poove Poochooda Vaa]]'' (1985)\n*''[[Karimedu Karuvayan]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Poovizhi Vasalile]]'' (1987)\n*''[[En Bommukutty Ammavukku]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Varusham Padhinaaru]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Arangetra Velai]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Gopura Vasalile]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Karpoora Mullai]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Kilipetchu Ketkava]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Ponnumani]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Ejamaan]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Rajakumaran (film)|Rajakumaran]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Nandhavana Theru]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Kadhalukku Mariyadhai]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Time (1999 film)|Time]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Kannukkul Nilavu]]'' (2000)\n*''[[Friends (2001 film)|Friends]]'' (2001)\n*''[[9 Nelalu|Kanden Seethaiyai]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Kasi (film)|Kasi]]'' (2001)\n*''[[En Mana Vaanil]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Magic Magic 3D]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Engal Anna]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Oru Naal Oru Kanavu]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Sadhu Miranda]]'' (2008)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1260911}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krishnan, Gokula}}\n[[Category:Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tamil film directors]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Tamil screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tirunelveli district]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image       =\n|imagesize   =\n|caption     = \n|name        = Gokula Krishnan\n|birth_date   = 1945\n|birth_place = [[Tirunelveli]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n|birth_name   = \n|death_date  = {{Death date|df=yes|2008|10|28}} (aged 63)\n|death_place = [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n|other_name(s)= \n|occupation  = Film director\n|spouse = Kavitha\n|yearsactive = 1982\u20132008\n|website    = \n|\n}}\n\n'''Gokula Krishnan''' was an [[India]]n film director, who has directed Tamil films. He was primarily active in the 1980s and early 1990s and is most noted for his work on films featuring actor [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]. He also extensively worked with Malayalam director [[Fazil (director)|Fazil]], when he made Tamil films, helping write dialogues.<ref>http://www.indiaglitz.com/director-gokulakrishna-passes-away-tamil-news-42616.html</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGokula Krishnan made his directorial debut in the early 1980s, before choosing to prioritise his work as a script-writer to Malayalam director [[Fazil (director)|Fazil]], when he made Tamil films. In the mid 1990s, Gokula Krishnan made three consecutive films with actor [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]]. ''[[Muthu Kaalai]]'' (1995), ''[[Poovarasan]]'' (1996) and ''[[Udhavikku Varalaamaa]]'' (1998) all fared poorly at the box office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Specials/97/Oct/a-z/atoz-5.htm |title=A-Z (V) |work=Indolink Tamil |accessdate=2012-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424003725/http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Specials/97/Oct/a-z/atoz-5.htm |archivedate=24 April 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHe died after a brief illness on 28 October 2008, leaving behind his wife, Kavitha.<ref>http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/oct-08-05/gokula-krishnan-29-10-08.html</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===As director===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse